editorial:
**Approach — trie + DP**: Insert dictionary into a trie. Define `dp[i]` = true if `s[i..]` is segmentable; `dp[n] = true`. Iterate `i` from `n-1` down to `0`: walk the trie from root following `s[i], s[i+1], ...`. Each time we hit a node with `isEnd`, that means `s[i..j]` is a dictionary word — if also `dp[j+1]` is true, set `dp[i]=true` and break.

```javascript
function canSegment(s, dictionary) {
  const root = { children: {}, isEnd: false };
  for (const w of dictionary) {
    let cur = root;
    for (const c of w) {
      if (!cur.children[c]) cur.children[c] = { children: {}, isEnd: false };
      cur = cur.children[c];
    }
    cur.isEnd = true;
  }
  const n = s.length;
  const dp = new Array(n + 1).fill(false);
  dp[n] = true;
  for (let i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    let cur = root;
    for (let j = i; j < n; j++) {
      const c = s[j];
      if (!cur.children[c]) break;
      cur = cur.children[c];
      if (cur.isEnd && dp[j + 1]) { dp[i] = true; break; }
    }
  }
  return dp[0];
}
```

**Time**: O(n * maxWordLen). **Space**: O(total dict chars + n).

