editorial:
**Idea — bit trie**: For each number, insert its 31-bit representation (MSB first) into a trie where each node has up to two children (`0` and `1`). Then for each number, traverse the trie greedily: at each bit, try to go to the OPPOSITE bit child (which would maximize that XOR bit); fall back to same bit if opposite is missing. Track the running XOR and the global max.

```javascript
function maximumXor(nums) {
  const root = [null, null];
  function insert(num) {
    let cur = root;
    for (let i = 30; i >= 0; i--) {
      const b = (num >> i) & 1;
      if (!cur[b]) cur[b] = [null, null];
      cur = cur[b];
    }
  }
  function query(num) {
    let cur = root;
    let xor = 0;
    for (let i = 30; i >= 0; i--) {
      const b = (num >> i) & 1;
      const want = 1 - b;
      if (cur[want]) {
        xor |= (1 << i);
        cur = cur[want];
      } else {
        cur = cur[b];
      }
    }
    return xor;
  }
  for (const n of nums) insert(n);
  let best = 0;
  for (const n of nums) best = Math.max(best, query(n));
  return best;
}
```

**Time**: O(N * 31). **Space**: O(N * 31).

Edge: when both nums are equal (e.g., [0,0]), every bit aligns → XOR is 0; the algorithm still works since we query with every element and find the same one (XOR with self = 0, but with the duplicate also = 0).

