editorial:
**Idea — trie + DP with 'parts used' counter**: Build a trie of all words. For each word `w`, run a DFS/DP from index 0: walk the trie, and every time we hit `isEnd` at index `j`, recurse on suffix starting at `j+1` requiring it to also fully decompose. Track `parts` — at least 2 needed. Crucially, the whole-word match (j == w.length on first segment with parts == 0) does NOT count by itself; we need parts >= 2 in total.

A cleaner equivalent: for each candidate `w`, ask whether it can be split into two pieces each of which is itself either in the dictionary or further decomposable — using memoized recursion with the trie as the membership check.

```javascript
function findConcatenatedWords(words) {
  const root = { children: {}, isEnd: false };
  for (const w of words) {
    let cur = root;
    for (const c of w) {
      if (!cur.children[c]) cur.children[c] = { children: {}, isEnd: false };
      cur = cur.children[c];
    }
    cur.isEnd = true;
  }
  function canForm(w, start, parts, memo) {
    if (start === w.length) return parts >= 2;
    const key = start + ',' + parts;
    if (memo.has(key)) return memo.get(key);
    let cur = root;
    for (let j = start; j < w.length; j++) {
      const c = w[j];
      if (!cur.children[c]) break;
      cur = cur.children[c];
      if (cur.isEnd && canForm(w, j + 1, parts + 1, memo)) {
        memo.set(key, true);
        return true;
      }
    }
    memo.set(key, false);
    return false;
  }
  const result = [];
  for (const w of words) {
    if (w.length === 0) continue;
    if (canForm(w, 0, 0, new Map())) result.push(w);
  }
  result.sort();
  return result;
}
```

**Time**: O(N * L^2) worst case. **Space**: O(total chars).

The `parts` counter ensures we only accept decompositions of two or more pieces — a single full match (the word itself) returns false.

