editorial:
**Idea — reverse-trie + two cases**: For each word w (index `idx`), we want some other word w' such that `w + w'` is a palindrome. Build a trie keyed by REVERSED words. While walking the trie following w from index 0, two cases reveal palindromes:

* **Case A** — the trie hits a complete word `w'` (its `wordIndex` set) at some position `i` while we're partway through w. That means `w' == reverse(w[0..i-1])`. If the remainder `w[i..end]` is itself a palindrome, then `w + w'` is a palindrome.
* **Case B** — w finishes the walk at some node. Any word `w''` whose reversed insertion passed through this node has `w` as a suffix of reverse(w''). If the EXTRA characters in reverse(w'') (the part still below this node) form a palindrome, then `w + w''` is a palindrome. We pre-store such indices in `palindromeBelow` during insertion.

```javascript
function palindromePairs(words) {
  function isPalin(s, l, r) {
    while (l < r) { if (s[l] !== s[r]) return false; l++; r--; }
    return true;
  }
  function makeNode() { return { children: {}, wordIndex: -1, palindromeBelow: [] }; }
  const root = makeNode();
  for (let idx = 0; idx < words.length; idx++) {
    const w = words[idx];
    let cur = root;
    for (let i = w.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
      if (isPalin(w, 0, i)) cur.palindromeBelow.push(idx);
      const c = w[i];
      if (!cur.children[c]) cur.children[c] = makeNode();
      cur = cur.children[c];
    }
    cur.wordIndex = idx;
    cur.palindromeBelow.push(idx);
  }
  const result = [];
  for (let idx = 0; idx < words.length; idx++) {
    const w = words[idx];
    let cur = root;
    for (let i = 0; i < w.length; i++) {
      if (cur.wordIndex !== -1 && cur.wordIndex !== idx && isPalin(w, i, w.length - 1)) {
        result.push([idx, cur.wordIndex]);
      }
      const c = w[i];
      if (!cur.children[c]) { cur = null; break; }
      cur = cur.children[c];
    }
    if (cur !== null) {
      for (const j of cur.palindromeBelow) {
        if (j !== idx) result.push([idx, j]);
      }
    }
  }
  result.sort((a, b) => a[0] !== b[0] ? a[0] - b[0] : a[1] - b[1]);
  return result;
}
```

**Time**: O(N * L^2) for trie build (palindrome checks per insert) + O(N * L) per query. **Space**: O(N * L).

