editorial:
**Idea — single-pass two-pointer**: Walk the query char by char with a pattern pointer `i`. If the current query char equals `pattern[i]`, advance `i`. Otherwise, the char must be lowercase (insertable); if it's uppercase, fail. At the end, `i` must have reached `pattern.length` for a match.

```javascript
function camelMatch(queries, pattern) {
  function matches(q, p) {
    let i = 0;
    for (const c of q) {
      if (i < p.length && c === p[i]) {
        i++;
      } else if (c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z') {
        return false;
      }
    }
    return i === p.length;
  }
  return queries.map(q => matches(q, pattern));
}
```

**Time**: O(sum of query lengths). **Space**: O(1) extra.

**Trie variant**: Insert pattern as a path. For each query, simulate the same matcher using the trie — useful if you have many patterns and want shared traversal, but with one pattern the two-pointer is cleaner.
